	//Ground Recipe Guide
"indappledgroves:indappledgrovesguide-inworldcrafting-title": "Game Mechanic: In-World Crafting",
"indappledgroves:indappledgrovesguide-inworldcrafting-text": 
"<font weight='bold' align='center'>In-World Crafting</font>
  In-World crafting takes place without the use of a grid recipe and is achieved by interacting with a block using a tool in a particular tool mode. 
  The blocks entry in the handbook will indicate the recipe and toolmode necessary to produce the desired result.",

	//Workstation Guide
"indappledgroves:indappledgrovesguide-workstations-title": "Game Mechanic: Workstation Crafting",
"indappledgroves:indappledgrovesguide-workstations-text": "<font weight='bold' align='center'>Workstation Crafting</font>
In Dappled Groves introduces new workstations to aid you in your woodworking endeavours. These workstations reduce the time required to complete woodworking operations such as chopping <a href=\"handbook://block-log-placed-birch-ud\">logs</a> into <a href=\"handbook://block-indappledgroves:logslab-birch-barked-down-free\">log slabs.</a>
<font weight='bold' align='center'>Workstations</font>
<font weight='bold' align='left'>Chopping Block</font>
   The first workstation most will craft is the <a href=\"handbook://block-indappledgroves:choppingblock-birch-east\">chopping block</a>.  Like all workstations, it speeds up the processes performed on it, and may provide access to recipes not available via in-world crafting in the future.
	 Currently it is used for <a href=\"handbook://toolmodes-indappledgroves\">chopping</a> and <a href=\"handbook://toolmodes-indappledgroves\">hewing</a> processes, but cannot be used to make additional chopping blocks.

<font weight='bold' align='left'>SawBuck</font>
	The sawbuck becomes available after you craft <a href=\"handbook://item-boards\">boards</a>. As with the chopping block, it speeds up processes performed on it, and is used for <a href=\"handbook://toolmodes-indappledgroves\">sawing</a> logs into boards.

<font weight='bold' align='left'>Saw Horse</font>
   This workstation isn't introduced in the current release. However, it will be integrated later providing a variety of woodworking options involving the use of planers and other tools.",

//Tool Modes Guide
"indappledgroves:indappledgrovesguide-toolmodes-title": "Game Mechanic: Tool Modes",
"indappledgroves:indappledgrovesguide-toolmodes-text": 
"<font weight='bold' align='center'>Tool Modes</font>
Tool modes are going to be an integral part of all tools introduced in this and future mods released by Aetherial Labs (Vinter Nachts modding group). These are part of the base game, primarily used for the smithy hammer and scythe. I've decided to expand upon their potential here.

<font weight='bold' align='center'>Basic Concepts</font>
Tool modes are now intrinsic parts of a new body of recipes I've included. They represent different ways you can interact with the blocks in the world, allowing you to produce different results by doing so. Currently there are three tool modes implemented, with a fourth currently disabled but planned to be implemented in In Dappled Groves. A fifth is planned.

<font weight='bold' align='center'>Tool Modes</font>

	<font weight='bold'>Chopping:</font> This mode is used when chopping wood into slabs, firewood, and sticks. May be changed to 'splitting' in a future revision.
	<font weight='bold'>Hewing:</font> This mode is used when shaping wood or 'peeling' it, such as when removing bark. Currently used only for peeling bark and creating chopping blocks from slabs.
	<font weight='bold'>Sawing:</font> This mode is solely used by saws, and is used when making boards out of logs.

	<font weight='bold' align='center'>Future Modes</font>
	<font weight='bold'>Planing:</font> Planing will be a mode used to process boards from a rough state into a smoothed state when more in-depth board making processes are introduced.
	<font weight='bold'>Riving:</font> Riving is a process by which logs can be split into shingles, beams, and various other pieces that require methods more precise than splitting with an axe or maul. A froe or frow is usually used for this process."
}